
Truth-Constrained Language Models: A Control-Theoretic and Optimization Framework for Eliminating Strategic Misalignment

ouadi Maakoul 

April 2026

---

Abstract

Large Language Models (LLMs) optimize objectives that often trade factual accuracy for fluency or helpfulness, yielding systematic hallucination under incentive misalignment. This thesis formalizes truthfulness as a hard constraint within a unified optimization and control framework. We develop a constrained alignment methodology based on primal-dual Direct Preference Optimization (PD-DPO) that solves a truth-constrained objective with rigorous suboptimality and constraint-violation bounds under Slater's condition and the Bradley-Terry preference model. At inference, we treat autoregressive token generation as a discrete dynamical system and enforce forward invariance of a truthfulness safe set via a discrete Control Barrier Function (CBF) safety filter. To overcome the recursive feasibility limitations of myopic CBFs and the computational intractability of N-step lookahead, we introduce Amortized Safety Critics via Hamilton-Jacobi (HJ) Reachability, which shifts the burden of long-horizon safety verification from inference-time search to training-time value function approximation. The Safety Critic learns the maximal achievable truthfulness from any state, enabling a control-invariant filter that guarantees the existence of a safe continuation path. The filter acts as a minimal-intervention projection on the token distribution, guaranteeing that every generated trajectory remains within a prescribed truthfulness threshold. We establish complete theoretical guarantees for saddle-point convergence, discrete-time forward invariance, robustness to bounded verifier error, compositional safety under multiple constraints, and approximation error bounds for the amortized safety critic. The framework elevates truth from a soft preference to a provably invariant dynamical property, providing a mathematically rigorous foundation for reliable language generation without reliance on empirical heuristics.

