Chapter 5: Discrete Control Barrier Functions for Autoregressive Generation

5.1 Dynamical System Formulation

We model autoregressive text generation as a discrete-time control system.

Definition 5.1.1 (State Space). The state at step k is the sequence of previously generated tokens s_k = (t_1,t_2,...,t_k) ∈ V^k. The initial state is s_0 = ∅.

Definition 5.1.2 (Control and Dynamics). The control at step k is the next token u_k = t_{k+1} ∈ V. The dynamics are deterministic:

s_{k+1} = f(s_k, u_k) = s_k ⊕ u_k

Definition 5.1.3 (Nominal Policy). A trained language model provides a conditional distribution P_nom(u|x,s_k). This is the nominal control policy.

5.2 Truth Barrier and Safe Set

Definition 5.2.1 (Verifier). Let V: X×Y → [0,1] be a verifier function that approximates the ground-truth truthfulness T(x,y).

Definition 5.2.2 (Barrier Function and Safe Set). Given threshold τ∈(0,1), define the barrier function:

h(s) = V(x,s) − τ

The safe set is C = {s∈Y: h(s) ≥ 0}.

5.3 Discrete CBF Condition for Text Generation

Definition 5.3.1 (Discrete CBF for Autoregressive Generation). h(s) is a discrete CBF for C with parameter γ∈[0,1) if for every safe state s∈C, ∃ u∈V such that:

h(s⊕u) ≥ γ h(s)

Lemma 5.3.1 (Recursive Feasibility Condition). A sufficient condition is max_{u∈V} h(s⊕u) ≥ γ h(s), ∀s∈C.

5.4 Safety Filter as KL Projection

Definition 5.4.1 (CBF Safety Filter). Given nominal distribution P(u|x,s), the safe distribution Q(u|x,s) is defined as:

Q(·|x,s) = argmin_{Q∈Δ(V)} D_KL(Q ∥ P(·|x,s)) s.t. E_{u∼Q}[h(s⊕u)] ≥ γ h(s)

Theorem 5.4.1 (Optimal Safe Distribution Form). The solution is:

Q(u|x,s) ∝ P(u|x,s) exp(μ h(s⊕u))

where μ≥0 is chosen to satisfy the constraint.

Corollary 5.4.1 (Hard-Constraint Approximation). For computational simplicity:

Q(u|x,s) = {P(u|x,s)/∑_{u'∈U_safe} P(u'|x,s) if u∈U_safe; 0 otherwise}

This approach is validated by Miyaoka et al. (2025), who propose a control-based framework leveraging CBF to ensure user-desirable text generation. Their framework applies the CBF safety filter to the predicted tokens from the baseline LLM as an add-on type mechanism, allowing alignment without fine-tuning the baseline model, and can directly incorporate any evaluation model regarding the desired alignment into the filter design. The framework has been implemented with open-source language models and demonstrates effective intervention for generating positive text.

5.5 Forward Invariance Guarantee

Theorem 5.5.1 (Forward Invariance of Safe Set). Suppose h(s_0) ≥ 0 and at each step, u_k is sampled from Q(·|x,s_k) with support contained in U_safe(s_k). Then for all k≥0, s_k∈C.

Proof. By induction. Base: h(s_0) ≥ 0. Inductive step: assume h(s_k) ≥ 0. Since u_k ∈ U_safe(s_k), h(s_k⊕u_k) ≥ γ h(s_k) ≥ 0. Thus s_{k+1}∈C. □

