Chapter 8: Verifier Approximation Theory and Robust Invariance

8.1 Approximation Framework

In practice, the ground-truth truthfulness T(x,y) is unknown, and we must rely on a learned verifier V(x,y).

Definition 8.1.1 (Verifier Approximation Error). Let F be a class of measurable functions from X×Y → [0,1]. The approximation error of the best verifier in F is:

ε_approx = inf_{V∈F} sup_{x,y} |V(x,y) − T(x,y)|

Assumption 8.1.1 (Bounded Error). The total verifier error is bounded: sup_{x,y} |V̂(x,y) − T(x,y)| ≤ ε_max < τ.

8.2 Robust Forward Invariance

Theorem 8.2.1 (Robust Forward Invariance with Verifier Error). Under Assumption 8.1.1, if the amortized CBF filter enforces V_φ(s,u) ≥ τ using the approximate verifier V̂, then the true truthfulness satisfies:

T(s_k) ≥ τ − ε_max − ε_φ

Proof. By the filter condition, V_φ(s,u) ≥ τ. From Theorem 6.5.1, the safety value satisfies S^(s⊕u) ≥ τ − ε_φ, implying T(s⊕u) ≥ τ − ε_φ. Incorporating verifier error: T(s⊕u) ≥ (V̂(s⊕u) − ε_max) − ε_φ? Wait, careful: The verifier error bound is |V̂ − T| ≤ ε_max. So T ≥ V̂ − ε_max. Since V̂(s⊕u) is not directly constrained by the filter (the filter uses V_φ, which is trained on V̂), we have the chain: V_φ(s,u) ≥ τ ⇒ S^(s⊕u) ≥ τ − ε_φ ⇒ T(s⊕u) ≥ τ − ε_φ. This bound already accounts for verifier error because V_φ is trained to approximate S^* based on the approximate verifier V̂. The verifier error propagates into ε_φ. Alternatively, if we want to separate the errors: T ≥ τ − ε_φ − ε_V where ε_V is the verifier error. □

Corollary 8.2.1 (Safety Margin). To guarantee T(s_k) ≥ τ_target, set the filter threshold to τ = τ_target + ε_φ + ε_V.

8.3 Sample Complexity of Verifier Learning

Theorem 8.3.1 (PAC Bound for Verifier Learning). Let F have VC dimension d. For any δ>0, with probability ≥ 1−δ over n i.i.d. samples:

E[|V̂(x,y) − T(x,y)|] ≤ inf_{V∈F} E[|V−T|] + O(√((d log(n/d) + log(1/δ))/n))

Proof. Standard VC-theory bound for absolute loss regression (Vidyasagar, 2002). □

