Chapter 9: Unified Convergence and Stability Analysis

9.1 Saddle-Point Characterization

Theorem 9.1.1 (Existence of Saddle Point). Under Assumptions 3.3.1-3.3.2, there exists a saddle point (π^,λ^) of L(π,λ) on Π×[0,∞).

Proof. Π is compact and convex. L is linear in π and linear in λ. By Sion's theorem, a saddle point exists. □

Theorem 9.1.2 (Structure of Optimal Policy). At the saddle point:

π^(y|x) = (1/Z^(x)) π_ref(y|x) exp((R(x,y) − λ^* C(x,y))/β)

9.2 Convergence of PD-DPO with Safety Critic

Theorem 9.2.1 (Joint Convergence). After K iterations of PD-DPO and critic training to error ε_φ, the expected truthfulness satisfies:

E[T(y)] ≥ τ − ε_V − ε_φ − O(1/√K)

Proof. Combine Theorem 4.3.2 (training violation O(1/√K)) with Theorem 7.2.1 (inference guarantee). □

9.3 Discrete-Time Lyapunov Stability

Definition 9.3.1 (Lyapunov Function). Define W(s) = τ − S^*(s). The amortized CBF condition ensures W(s_{k+1}) ≤ γ' W(s_k) for some γ'∈[0,1).

Theorem 9.3.1 (Asymptotic Stability). The safe set C^*_τ is asymptotically stable in the sense of Lyapunov.

Proof. From the Bellman equation, S^(s) = max_u min(T(s⊕u), S^(s⊕u)). If S^(s) ≥ τ, then there exists u with S^(s⊕u) ≥ τ, so W(s⊕u) ≤ 0. The contraction property follows from the structure of the value function. □

