Chapter 10: Theoretical Limitations and Open Problems

10.1 Limitations

10.1.1 Non-Convex Policy Parameterization. The policy π_θ is parameterized by a deep neural network, making the objective non-convex in θ. Our guarantees apply to the function space Π but do not guarantee global optimality in the parameter space. Recent work on optimistic primal-dual methods has made progress on last-iterate convergence under parameterized policies.

10.1.2 Safety Critic Approximation Error. The amortized critic introduces an additional error term ε_φ. Bounding this error theoretically requires assumptions on the function class and data coverage. In practice, the critic may overestimate safety in out-of-distribution states.

10.1.3 Verifier Expressivity. The robust invariance guarantee degrades linearly with verifier error ε_V. High-stakes applications require highly accurate verifiers.

10.1.4 Computational Cost of Critic Training. Training the safety critic requires generating rollouts and computing bootstrapped targets, which adds computational overhead compared to myopic CBF filters. However, this cost is amortized over inference.

10.1.5 Path Recovery Mechanism. The constrained beam search fallback may be invoked when U_amortized is empty. Its effectiveness depends on the beam width and depth limits.

10.2 Open Problems

10.2.1 Non-Convex Primal-Dual Dynamics. Establish rigorous convergence guarantees for primal-dual methods applied to neural policy parameterizations under the PL or KL conditions.

10.2.2 Multi-Step Safety Critics. Extend the critic to predict safety over variable horizons, enabling adaptive lookahead based on uncertainty.

10.2.3 Adaptive Thresholds. Design mechanisms to dynamically adjust τ based on prompt difficulty and verifier confidence.

10.2.4 Integration with Retrieval-Augmented Generation. Incorporate external knowledge retrieval within the safety critic to ground truthfulness assessments in verifiable sources.

10.2.5 Formal Verification of Learned Critics. Develop methods to provide formal guarantees on the approximation error ε_φ, perhaps via interval bound propagation or certified training.

