Chapter 11: Conclusion

This thesis has presented a mathematically rigorous framework for enforcing truthfulness as a hard constraint in language model alignment. The key contributions include:

1. A complete formalization of truth-constrained alignment as a saddle-point problem with strong duality.
2. A primal-dual DPO algorithm with O(1/√K) convergence guarantees, validated by recent work showing the effectiveness of dual-based alignment methods in finding optimal constrained LLM policies.
3. A discrete-time CBF framework for token-level safety filtering, with proven forward invariance and minimal intervention properties, building on established control-theoretic approaches for LLM alignment.
4. Amortized Safety Critics via Hamilton-Jacobi Reachability: A novel extension that addresses the recursive feasibility and computational challenges of myopic CBF filters by learning a safety value function that captures long-horizon feasibility, drawing on principles from HJ reachability analysis and recent advances in learning-based reachability for high-dimensional systems.
5. End-to-end robustness guarantees showing that bounded approximation errors in the verifier and safety critic translate to bounded truthfulness degradation.
6. Compositional theory for multi-constraint safety filters.

The amortized safety critic framework represents a significant advance over myopic CBF approaches. By shifting the computational burden of N-step lookahead from inference time to training time, we enable real-time generation with long-horizon safety guarantees. The Safety Critic learns the maximal achievable truthfulness from any state, ensuring control invariance and eliminating deadlock scenarios where the model would otherwise be forced into hallucination. The approximation error bounds provide a principled characterization of how critic inaccuracy propagates to end-to-end safety guarantees.

All results are established through rigorous definitions, theorems, and proofs. The framework provides a foundational theoretical architecture for reliable language generation, elevating truth from a heuristic objective to a provably invariant system property.

Future work will address the limitations identified in Chapter 10, including non-convex convergence analysis, formal verification of learned critics, and empirical validation of the theoretical guarantees in realistic language model deployments. The integration of amortized safety critics with retrieval-augmented generation and adaptive threshold mechanisms represents promising directions for extending the framework to more complex and dynamic environments.

